      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 used under ISO 9001:2015 QMS with documented V&V test suite for structural FEA. Software version controlled and traceable.",
      "rationale": "The simulation was performed using Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1, a commercially validated solver operating under the sponsor's ISO 9001:2015 quality management system. Release notes, patch history, and regression test suite results are archived. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2 for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS LE1 and LE10 series reproduced to within 0.5% of analytical solution. Contact element patch test passed.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical code verification was demonstrated via NAFEMS benchmark suite LE1, LE10, and NL1 contact patch test. All results within 0.5% of reference solutions. Code verification is documented in the sponsor's FEA platform qualification report Rev 4.2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in peak von Mises stress and <1% change in construct stiffness between medium and fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation GCI < 1%.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh refinement study was conducted across three mesh densities (coarse: 45k elements, medium: 180k elements, fine: 720k elements). QoIs converged monotonically. GCI for stiffness was 0.4% and for yield force was 0.7%. Fine mesh adopted for production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual norm < 1e-4 at each load step. Energy convergence criterion < 1e-5. No unconverged load steps in production runs.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analyses used full Newton-Raphson iteration with force convergence tolerance 1e-4 and energy tolerance 1e-5. All 11 simulation cases converged without bisection failures. Solver log files archived for traceability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact definition by a second qualified analyst. Checklist-based review documented.",
      "rationale": "A peer review checklist covering boundary conditions, load application, material assignments, and contact pair definitions was completed by a second senior FEA analyst independent of the primary modeler. All checklist items passed. Review documented in project record PR-2025-047."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic model with isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V. Contact modeled with augmented Lagrangian frictional interface (mu=0.2). Model form supported by prior published validations for equivalent loading scenarios.",
      "rationale": "The elastic-plastic continuum model with von Mises yield criterion and isotropic hardening is well-established for Ti-6Al-4V under quasi-static bending. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) is consistent with published tribology data for titanium-on-titanium interfaces. The intermediate literature synthesis node (vr-intermediate-literature-synthesis) was used to bound prior model form error expectations across the relevant loading regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, yield strength, UTS, hardening slope) measured from coupon specimens cut from the same lot as test constructs. Geometric inputs from CMM measurements of as-built screws.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus were characterized from five tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture the test constructs (mean E=114.2 GPa, sigma_y=897 MPa). Screw geometry was digitized via CMM to ±5 micron accuracy. All input parameters are traceable to calibrated measurement records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from same production lot, tested across two independent laboratories. Sample size provides 80% power to detect 10% QoI difference at alpha=0.05.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from a single production lot (lot number 2024-NC-7.5-042) and distributed across two independent test laboratories (Lab A: n=6, Lab B: n=5). Power analysis confirmed 80% power to detect a 10% mean difference in stiffness. Inter-laboratory reproducibility was assessed via ANOVA (p=0.43, no significant lab effect)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 setup including loading angle, fixture geometry, and displacement rate. Multiple loading rates or conditions would be required for level 3.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted strictly per ASTM F1717-21 at a single quasi-static displacement rate of 5 mm/min. Only one loading condition (compression-bending at standard F1717 geometry) was evaluated. A second loading condition (e.g., torsion or fatigue) would be required to achieve level 3. This factor is below the required level and is flagged as a credibility gap; the gap is accepted given that the intended use is limited to quasi-static compression-bending prediction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to experimental test specimen and setup parameters within stated measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Equivalency was established by mapping each FEA input parameter to its experimental counterpart with documented uncertainty: geometry (CMM ±5 µm vs. nominal drawing), material (coupon test ±2% vs. FEA input), friction coefficient (literature range 0.15–0.25 vs. FEA 0.20). Sensitivity analysis confirmed QoI insensitivity to friction coefficient variation across this range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric (validation uncertainty normalized error). Pass criterion: E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs. Additionally, percent difference < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 0.82, yield force 1.14, force at 40 mm 0.91. All three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10%. The validation uncertainty budget includes measurement uncertainty, inter-lab variability, and simulation numerical uncertainty. Achieved level 4 reflects quantitative uncertainty-normalized comparison with documented uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical failure mode (screw or rod fracture under cyclic bending) and to the regulatory submission acceptance criteria.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the FDA guidance document for pedicle screw system 510(k) submissions. Each QoI maps directly to a clinically relevant failure mode: stiffness to load sharing, yield force to permanent deformation onset, and force at 40 mm to ultimate structural capacity. QoI relevance is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test) is the same test standard referenced in the COU. Device geometry, material, and loading mode in validation match the COU exactly.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is conducted on the identical device design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), under the identical test standard (ASTM F1717-21), with the identical loading mode (static compression-bending) as the COU. There is no extrapolation of loading mode, geometry, or material. Relevance of validation activities to the COU is rated at the maximum achievable level for a single-condition study."
    }
